  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address **money laundering** at both the **federal** and **state** levels in the United States, as well as internationally. Below is an overview of key laws and frameworks:\n\n---\n\n### **United States Federal Statutes**\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**\n   - Requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports (e.g., Currency Transaction Reports [CTRs] and Suspicious Activity Reports [SARs]) to help detect and prevent money laundering.\n\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**\n   - Criminalizes money laundering as a federal offense.\n   - Includes provisions for prosecuting individuals and entities involved in laundering proceeds from illegal activities.\n\n3. **Annunzio-Wylie Anti-Money Laundering Act of 1992**\n   - Expands the BSA to require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering (AML) programs and report suspicious transactions.\n\n4. **USA PATRIOT Act (2001)**\n   - Strengthens AML measures by requiring stricter due diligence, enhancing information sharing between financial institutions and law enforcement, and expanding the scope of AML requirements to include non-bank financial institutions.\n\n5. **Intelligence Reform and Terrorism Prevention Act of 2004**\n   - Enhances anti-money laundering efforts by addressing vulnerabilities in the financial system that could be exploited by terrorists.\n\n---\n\n### **International Frameworks**\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - An intergovernmental body that sets global standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats.\n   - Member countries are required to implement FATF recommendations into their national laws.\n\n2. **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**\n   - Requires signatory countries to criminalize money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n\n3. **EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**\n   - The European Union has issued several directives to combat money laundering and terrorist financing, requiring member states to adopt AML measures.\n\n---\n\n### **State Laws**\n   - Many U.S. states have enacted laws to address money laundering, often mirroring federal statutes but tailored to state-specific needs.\n\n---\n\nThese statutes and frameworks aim to prevent criminals from disguising the origins of illegally obtained funds, deter financial crimes, and protect the integrity of the global financial system. Violations of these laws can result in severe penalties, including fines, forfeiture of assets, and imprisonment.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
